      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Below Market Value to Family in Queensland: Legal, Tax, and Practical Considerations
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling to a family member below market value is legal in Queensland, but it triggers transfer duty on market value, CGT on market value, and potential Centrelink gifting consequences. Here is how to structure the transaction properly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Non-arm's length family property transactions are common and largely invisible. A parent sells a home to a daughter at a generous discount to help her onto the property ladder. Siblings transfer jointly inherited property from one to the other at a figure closer to the mortgage balance than the market value. An elderly parent sells the family home to a son for a fraction of its worth as part of succession planning. These transactions are entirely legal in Queensland and often achieve sensible family outcomes. What they are not, however, is free of tax and regulatory consequences.</p>

      <p>The common mistake is to assume that because the sale is within the family, normal property tax rules do not apply. They apply fully, and in several respects they apply more strictly than in an arm's length sale. If you are considering selling to a family member below market value, understanding the tax, duty, and Centrelink implications before you sign anything is essential. Handled properly, the transaction can still be worthwhile. Handled carelessly, the tax consequences can quickly exceed the intended benefit to the family member.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework</h2>
      <p>Selling at a price below market value is allowed in Queensland. There is no statutory requirement that private property transactions be conducted at arm's length or at market value. Two parties can agree to any price they choose, and the transfer can be registered in the usual way. The Queensland Titles Registry does not query the price on a transfer; it simply records the change of ownership.</p>

      <p>What changes in a non-arm's length transaction is not whether it can proceed, but how the tax and regulatory systems assess it. Revenue and social security authorities apply specific rules designed to prevent non-arm's length sales from being used to avoid tax or artificially reduce assets. Those rules do not prevent the sale, but they reshape its cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Transfer duty is calculated on market value</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Office of State Revenue calculates transfer duty on the higher of the contract price or the market value of the property. This is a specific anti-avoidance rule, and it applies to every transfer, not just family transactions. In an arm's length sale, the contract price and the market value are typically close enough that the rule has no practical effect. In a non-arm's length family sale, the difference can be significant.</p>

      <p>A concrete example: a mother sells her Morningside home to her daughter for $500,000 at a time when the genuine market value of the home is $900,000. The contract price is $500,000, but transfer duty is assessed on $900,000. The duty does not follow the discount. The daughter, who is the buyer and typically pays the duty, is assessed on the full market value even though she only paid $500,000 for the property. On a $900,000 Queensland property, transfer duty sits in the low tens of thousands. The daughter may well be prepared to pay that, but she needs to know it is coming.</p>

      <p>The OSR determines market value either from an independent valuation provided by the parties or from its own assessment if the parties cannot produce a credible valuation. This is why professional valuations are essential in family transactions: they give the OSR a defensible figure to work from and prevent the OSR substituting a higher figure of its own.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">CGT applies on market value for the seller</h2>
      <p>The capital gains tax position is equally important and often overlooked. The Australian Taxation Office applies the market value substitution rule for non-arm's length transactions. The seller's capital gain is calculated using the market value at the date of the transaction, not the price paid by the buyer.</p>

      <p>To continue the example above, the mother who sold at $500,000 is treated for CGT purposes as having sold at $900,000. If the home was her main residence for the whole period of ownership, the main residence exemption is likely to apply and the gain is exempt from CGT. If the home was an investment property, or was her main residence for only part of the period of ownership, the CGT liability is assessed on the $900,000 figure. In the investment property case, this can create a tax liability on gains the seller never received in cash, which is the most painful version of the rule.</p>

      <p>The main residence exemption is the most common reason family sales proceed without a CGT problem, but it is not automatic. A property used for income-producing purposes at any point during ownership, a property that was rented out for a period while the owner lived elsewhere, or a property larger than two hectares may all have partial or no main residence exemption. These cases need specific tax advice before the transaction proceeds.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Centrelink gifting rules bite hard</h2>
      <p>For pension recipients, the Centrelink treatment of a below-market sale can have the largest impact of all. Selling an asset for less than its market value is treated as "gifting" under the deprivation rules. The difference between the market value and the sale price is treated as if it were still an asset of the pensioner for five years from the date of the transaction.</p>

      <p>In the example, the mother has effectively gifted $400,000 of value to her daughter. Centrelink will treat the mother as still owning $400,000 worth of deemed assets for five years, which will be included in the assets test and the income test through deeming. Depending on her current pension entitlement, this can reduce the pension substantially or eliminate it altogether for the full five-year period.</p>

      <p>The gifting rules allow a small annual gifting threshold (currently around $10,000 per financial year, subject to a $30,000 five-year cap) before the deprivation rules apply in full. For transfers of property worth hundreds of thousands of dollars, those thresholds are trivial. The five-year clock does not reset if the recipient later pays more money. Once the gift is made, the deemed asset sits on the pensioner's record for the full period.</p>

      <p>This is the single most frequent reason family property transactions backfire on the seller. A pensioner who relies heavily on their Centrelink payments can see their income drop substantially for five years because of a well-intentioned below-market sale to a family member. Specific advice from a Centrelink-experienced financial planner, before the sale, is essential in any case where the seller receives any form of means-tested government payment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to document the transaction properly</h2>
      <p>Proper documentation is the minimum standard for any family property sale. Start with an independent valuation from a certified practising valuer. Not an agent appraisal, not a comparative market analysis, not a real estate website estimate. A certified valuation gives you a defensible figure for the OSR, for the ATO, and for Centrelink, and removes the risk of any authority substituting its own higher figure.</p>

      <p>Prepare a formal contract of sale using the REIQ template, just as you would in an arm's length transaction. Engage solicitors for both parties. Family members do not need to use separate solicitors by law, but the risk of conflict of interest and the long-term importance of clean documentation make separate representation the professional standard. Yes, it costs more. It is also the difference between a transaction that is defensible if the ATO or Centrelink reviews it and one that is not.</p>

      <p>Document the non-arm's length nature of the transaction in a file note or side letter, signed by both parties, recording the family relationship, the market valuation figure, the sale price, and the reasons for the discount. If there is a surrounding family agreement (a life tenancy for the parent, a right of first refusal, a loan-back arrangement), document that too, in clear language, with legal advice.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The gift alternative</h2>
      <p>A direct gift of property (transfer at zero consideration) is sometimes considered as an alternative to a below-market sale. The tax consequences are similar: transfer duty is still calculated on market value, CGT is still calculated on market value for the giver, and the Centrelink gifting rules still apply to the full market value of the property.</p>

      <p>The main difference is administrative rather than financial. A gift is simpler to document and does not require the recipient to find finance for any portion of the purchase price. For parents transferring property to adult children who have no intention of servicing a mortgage, a gift can be cleaner than a nominal sale. The tax cost is the same; the paperwork is lighter.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The loan-based alternative</h2>
      <p>One structure that can achieve a similar economic outcome with better tax and Centrelink treatment is to sell the property at market value and provide the family member with a loan for part of the purchase price. The mother in the example above could sell to her daughter for the full $900,000, receive $500,000 in cash, and lend the daughter the remaining $400,000 at a low or zero interest rate.</p>

      <p>This structure avoids the market value substitution rule for transfer duty (duty is still calculated on the contract price, but the contract price is the market value, so there is no discrepancy). It avoids the CGT market value substitution rule. It does not trigger the Centrelink gifting rules on the full $400,000, because the mother still has a loan asset of $400,000 on her balance sheet.</p>

      <p>The catch is that the loan has to be a genuine loan, not a sham. Documented in writing, with repayment terms, security if appropriate, and a realistic interest rate or an enforceable commercial justification for zero interest. If the parent later forgives the loan, the forgiveness itself is treated as a gift, with Centrelink implications from that date forward. But while the loan is in place, the parent's balance sheet and pension position are protected, and the family member has effectively received the same economic benefit as a below-market sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Non-arm's length family property sales are legitimate, common, and sometimes the right choice. They are not, however, the cheap and simple alternative to an arm's length transaction that families often assume. The tax and regulatory consequences are real, sometimes substantial, and usually require professional advice to structure well.</p>

      <p>Before proceeding with any below-market family sale, get an independent valuation, get specific tax advice on the CGT position, get Centrelink advice if any party to the transaction receives means-tested payments, and use proper legal representation. Consider the loan-based alternative seriously, because for many families it achieves the same outcome with materially lower cost. The family-can-work-it-out-without-lawyers instinct is almost always the wrong one in these transactions. The cost of getting the structure right is a small fraction of the cost of getting it wrong.</p>

